From: PS4 Linux Baikal Port <noreply@ps4-linux>
Subject: [PATCH] amdgpu: v49 - clobber dp_extclk on Liverpool so picker selects a real PPLL

The v48 trace caught the next blocker after AdjustDisplayPll/SetPixelClock
were both made to run cleanly:

  ps4_atom: SetPixelClock IN frev=1 crev=6 crtc=0 clock=148500 pll=255 ref=2 fb=118 frac=8 post=22 enc_id=30 enc_mode=0 bpc=8 ss=1
  ps4_atom: SetPixelClock OUT r=0

`pll=255` is `ATOM_PPLL_INVALID`. ATOM v6 SetPixelClock returns r=0 cleanly
when ucPpll=0xFF because there's nothing to program — no PLL gets
configured, no GPU clock is generated, the bridge's cq_wait_set polls for
a DP signal that never arrives (3-second timeout, screen dark).

The picker is `dce_v8_0_pick_pll` at `dce_v8_0.c:2174-2177`:

  if (ENCODER_MODE_IS_DP(...)) {
      if (adev->clock.dp_extclk)
          /* skip PPLL programming if using ext clock */
          return ATOM_PPLL_INVALID;

`adev->clock.dp_extclk` is read from VBIOS firmware_info_21
(`usUniphyDPModeExtClkFreq`) at `amdgpu_atombios.c:707`. Sony's Starsha2
VBIOS advertises a non-zero value, telling amdgpu "the DP PHY is clocked
from an external reference, don't bother programming a PPLL". That's
correct for some retail CIK boards that have a dedicated DP ref clock IC,
but it's wrong on PS4 — the GPU's DisplayPort output goes to the MN864729
HDMI bridge over an internal trace, and there is no external reference
clock routed to Liverpool's UNIPHY block. The PHY must be driven by an
on-chip PPLL.

When `dp_extclk` is non-zero, two things go wrong simultaneously:

  1. dce_v8_0_pick_pll returns ATOM_PPLL_INVALID, so SetPixelClock has no
     PLL to program (v48 confirmed pll=255).
  2. atombios_encoders.c (lines 940, 1000, 1067) selects
     ucRefClkSource=2 (external) for the DIG PHY's DP_PHY_INSTANCE
     args, instead of ucRefClkSource=pll_id. Even if the picker
     returned a valid PPLL, the PHY would still try to use the
     non-existent external clock.

Both reads are gated on the same `dp_extclk != 0` test. Clobbering it to
0 for Liverpool/Gladius right after the VBIOS read fixes both with one
override.

Effect on the picker after the clobber (v49 expected):

  ENCODER_MODE_IS_DP(enc_mode) → true
  adev->clock.dp_extclk → 0 (clobbered)
  amdgpu_pll_get_shared_dp_ppll(crtc) → ATOM_PPLL_INVALID (no other DP CRTC)
  fall through to CIK allocation block (line 2202+)
  pll_in_use = 0 (fresh boot)
  return ATOM_PPLL2 (== 1)

So `amdgpu_crtc->pll_id = 1`, ATOM SetPixelClock v6 receives `ucPpll=1`,
and Sony's bytecode programs whatever the *real* PPLL2 hardware is on
Liverpool (not the phantom mmDCCG_PLL_* registers from the v45 patch).
The DIG encoder DP PHY ref source becomes pll_id=1 (PPLL2) too, so the
PHY clock chain is internally consistent.

Two debug prints added for visibility:

  - In amdgpu_atombios_get_clock_info, print the VBIOS value before the
    clobber.
  - In dce_v8_0_pick_pll on Liverpool/Gladius, print enc_mode + dp_extclk
    + asic_type so we can see the picker decision in the next boot log.

Expected v49 trace markers in next boot:

  ps4_atom: VBIOS dp_extclk=<NNN> (PS4 forces 0 on Liverpool/Gladius)
  ps4_atom: dce_v8_0_pick_pll enc_mode=0 dp_extclk=0 asic=<liverpool>
  ps4_atom: SetPixelClock IN frev=1 crev=6 crtc=0 clock=148500 pll=1 ref=2 fb=118 frac=8 post=22 ...
  ps4_atom: SetPixelClock OUT r=0
  ps4_bridge_enable: cq_exec=20 (with the 3-second wait shrunk dramatically)

If the bridge cq_wait_set still hangs, the next investigation would be
the DIG/DP TX programming itself (link training, lane setup) since the
PLL is now confirmed programmed.

---
--- a/drivers/gpu/drm/amd/amdgpu/amdgpu_atombios.c
+++ b/drivers/gpu/drm/amd/amdgpu/amdgpu_atombios.c
@@ -706,6 +706,23 @@
 		}
 		adev->clock.dp_extclk =
 			le16_to_cpu(firmware_info->info_21.usUniphyDPModeExtClkFreq);
+		/* v49 (PS4 Liverpool/Gladius): Sony's Starsha2 VBIOS sets a non-zero
+		 * dp_extclk in the firmware_info table, advertising "DP PHY is
+		 * clocked from external source, don't program a PPLL." That's wrong
+		 * on PS4 — the MN864729 bridge needs a real DP signal driven by a
+		 * PPLL, and there's no usable external DP ref clock routed to
+		 * Liverpool's UNIPHY block. With dp_extclk non-zero,
+		 * dce_v8_0_pick_pll returns ATOM_PPLL_INVALID for DP encoders, and
+		 * atombios_encoders.c chooses ucRefClkSource=2 (external) for the
+		 * DIG PHY — both producing no GPU clock. Clobber to 0 here so all
+		 * 6 downstream consumers see a coherent "no external clock, use a
+		 * PPLL" picture. v48 trace confirmed pll=255 was reaching ATOM
+		 * SetPixelClock; this fix makes the picker return PPLL2 instead. */
+		pr_info("ps4_atom: VBIOS dp_extclk=%u (PS4 forces 0 on Liverpool/Gladius)\n",
+			adev->clock.dp_extclk);
+		if (adev->asic_type == CHIP_LIVERPOOL ||
+		    adev->asic_type == CHIP_GLADIUS)
+			adev->clock.dp_extclk = 0;
 		adev->clock.current_dispclk = adev->clock.default_dispclk;

 		adev->clock.max_pixel_clock = le16_to_cpu(firmware_info->info.usMaxPixelClock);
--- a/drivers/gpu/drm/amd/amdgpu/dce_v8_0.c
+++ b/drivers/gpu/drm/amd/amdgpu/dce_v8_0.c
@@ -2170,8 +2170,18 @@
 	struct amdgpu_device *adev = drm_to_adev(dev);
 	u32 pll_in_use;
 	int pll;
+	int enc_mode = amdgpu_atombios_encoder_get_encoder_mode(amdgpu_crtc->encoder);

-	if (ENCODER_MODE_IS_DP(amdgpu_atombios_encoder_get_encoder_mode(amdgpu_crtc->encoder))) {
+	/* v49: trace picker decision so we can see if Liverpool gets a real
+	 * PPLL after the dp_extclk clobber. Expected on PS4: enc_mode=0 (DP),
+	 * dp_extclk=0 (forced by amdgpu_atombios.c v49 fix), picker falls
+	 * through to amdgpu_pll_get_shared_dp_ppll (returns INVALID on first
+	 * DP CRTC) then to the CIK allocation block returning ATOM_PPLL2. */
+	if (adev->asic_type == CHIP_LIVERPOOL || adev->asic_type == CHIP_GLADIUS)
+		pr_info("ps4_atom: dce_v8_0_pick_pll enc_mode=%d dp_extclk=%u asic=%d\n",
+			enc_mode, adev->clock.dp_extclk, adev->asic_type);
+
+	if (ENCODER_MODE_IS_DP(enc_mode)) {
 		if (adev->clock.dp_extclk)
 			/* skip PPLL programming if using ext clock */
 			return ATOM_PPLL_INVALID;
